# day49-of-50-blog-posts



## Day 49: Do you have a set of rules or guidelines for your life? Did you write them? Why do you use them?

I don't usually bring up my belief system, but since that's the point of this prompt, I'll share.
I identify as a Humanist because their rules and tenets make sense to me.
Humanism, to me, emphasizes living in the present, recognizing our personal freedom, and understanding that our lives are meaningful when shared with others.
I also find resonance in Tao philosophy and Stoicism. Even while reading the parable of the sower, the idea of 'god being change' really made sense.

Growing up, I was always drawn to the idea of being the author of my own life (Even though the idea of Fate vs Freewill keeps me up at night, lol).

I haven't written my own set of rules; instead, I've taken what makes sense to me and discarded what doesn't. This pragmatic approach allows me to embrace
diverse philosophies and live a life that feels authentic to me.

For instance, I've found that accepting diverse approaches to life, as long as they do no harm, has made me more open-minded and tolerant.
People being 'weird' is okay by me and im proud to know so many vibrant people in my life.

So, while I don't have a neatly packaged set of guidelines, I have a framework that works for me. It's a blend of Humanism, Tao philosophy,
Stoicism, and even a bit of religious parable. This mix has helped me navigate life's challenges and find meaning in my experiences.

After all, we only have one life, so our attention should be on here focused on now.


